<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="un2026i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un2" href="#un2026">UN2: </a>  <a href="../../FF/unbs/un2all.htm#un2026i"> (VI.D.7) 26(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> smithereens</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Dead as a door-nail (<i>Peoples&apos;</i>; from Ireland). Dead as O&apos;Donnel; on all fours with &lsquo;I&apos;ll smash you into <mark>smithereens</mark>&rsquo;&mdash;that is to say, Smithers&apos; Ruins&mdash;S. having had his house pulled about his ears. O&apos;Donnel being dead and Smithers no longer alive, the two folk -phrases become, the one anglicized into &lsquo;door-nail&rsquo;, the other into a powerful word representing complete destruction, one which is heard to this day amongst the Irish lower classes wherever found. <small> J. Reading Ware, <a name="JRWP" href="/udra/udex.htm#JRWP"><cite title="source">Passing English of the Victorian Era</cite></a> (1909), 105</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c16250d" href="../../../F/FF/fnbs/c16all.htm#c16250d">VI.C.16:250(d)</a> </dd> </dd></dl>
